  "prompt": "How many First Ladies have refused to live in the White House?",
  "response": "As of October 2023, **all First Ladies of the United States have lived in the White House** at some point during their time in the role, even if they were not always enthusiastic about it. However, there are a few notable instances where First Ladies minimized their time in the White House or expressed reluctance:\n\n1. **Martha Washington (1789\u20131797)** \u2013 While she lived in the presidential residences in New York and Philadelphia (the capital before Washington, D.C.), she reportedly did not enjoy her time as First Lady and longed to return to Mount Vernon.\n\n2. **Abigail Adams (1797\u20131801)** \u2013 She spent much of her time in Quincy, Massachusetts, away from the White House, which was still under construction during her husband\u2019s presidency.\n\n3. **Letitia Tyler (1841\u20131842)** \u2013 She was the first First Lady to live in the White House but was in poor health and largely stayed in her private quarters, avoiding public duties.\n\n4. **Margaret Taylor (1849\u20131850)** \u2013 She had little interest in being First Lady and delegated many responsibilities to her daughter.\n\n5. **Jane Pierce (1853\u20131857)** \u2013 She stayed away from the White House for the first two years of her husband\u2019s presidency, grieving the loss of her son.\n\nWhile these First Ladies may have had reservations or minimized their time in the White House, none outright refused to live there permanently. The tradition of living in the White House has been upheld by all subsequent First Ladies.",
